#!hexa strict
// qmirror/clifford-data-regression/module/clifford_data_regression.hexa
//
// @tool(slug="qmirror_clifford_data_regression", desc="Czarnik-Arrasmith-Coles-Cincio Clifford Data Regression (Quantum 5, 592 (2021) / arXiv:2005.10189). Pure-hexa engine_aer kernel: EXACT 2^n state-vector simulation of the IDEAL CDR error-mitigation protocol on a small n=4 parameterized circuit (depth 6 ; ~16 single-qubit + 2-qubit gates) containing ONE non-Clifford R_z(theta_target) rotation; target observable <O> = <Z_0>. Training set: M=64 near-Clifford circuits with the R_z(theta_target) replaced by R_z(k * pi/2) for k drawn uniformly from {0,1,2,3} via a deterministic LCG seed (each training circuit is Clifford in EVERY gate -- the paper's K=0 training subset). For each training circuit the EXACT noiseless expectation y_i = <O>_exact is computed from the 2^n state vector (engine_aer); the 'noisy' expectation x_i = <O>_noisy is the analytic depolarising-channel image x_i = (1 - p) * y_i (textbook for traceless Pauli O on rho -> (1-p)*rho + p*I/2^n). Analytic OLS fits slope b = Sum((x_i - x_bar)(y_i - y_bar)) / Sum((x_i - x_bar)^2) and intercept a = y_bar - b * x_bar; mitigated <O>_target_mit = a + b * <O>_target_noisy. Five falsifier invariants (F1-F5): identity regression at p=0 (|b-1| < 1e-9 AND |a| < 1e-9), MSE_mitigated <= MSE_raw on a 32-circuit held-out set at p=0.1, MSE_mitigated < 0.95 * MSE_raw at p=0.05 (margin > 5%), no NaN/Inf in slope/intercept, and <psi|psi> drift < 1e-9 across every training+test+target circuit. Genuine ceiling ~ n <= 8 (small registers are the natural CDR regime; 2^n state-vector wall is far below; the bottleneck is the (M_train * (gate_count + 2^n)) wall in the LCG-seeded training-set sweep, which scales linearly in M and 2^n).")
// @usage(hexa run clifford-data-regression/module/clifford_data_regression.hexa --selftest)
// @sentinel(__QMIRROR_CLIFFORD_DATA_REGRESSION__ <PASS|FAIL>)
// @resolver-bypass(reason="Selftest is a pure-hexa EXACT 2^n=16-amplitude state-vector simulation of the Czarnik-Arrasmith-Coles-Cincio 2021 Clifford Data Regression error-mitigation protocol on a small n=4 parameterized circuit. No qiskit, no python bridge, no live QRNG -- a deterministic LCG seeds the training-set non-Clifford-to-Clifford angle replacement and the held-out test-set angle draw; the noise channel is the analytic depolarising-channel image on the EXACT noiseless <O> (closed form for traceless Pauli observables). The verdict is the closed-form OLS slope/intercept against the (x,y)=(noisy, exact) training pairs and the MSE comparison on the test set.")
//
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  PAPER DEEP-DIVE  (2026-05-17; arXiv:2005.10189 + Quantum 5, 592 (2021))
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  PRIMARY ANCHOR -- Piotr Czarnik, Andrew Arrasmith, Patrick J. Coles,
//      Lukasz Cincio, "Error mitigation with Clifford quantum-circuit
//      data", Quantum 5, 592 (2021); arXiv:2005.10189.
//
//  PROTOCOL (paper §II + §IV.A, Algorithm 1):
//
//    (1) Pick a target circuit C_target of n qubits and depth d, with K
//        non-Clifford parameterized gates (e.g. R_z(theta) with non-multiple-
//        of-pi/2 theta). The target observable <O> is a Pauli string (here
//        O = Z_0, a single-qubit-Z on q0).
//
//    (2) Construct a training set of M near-Clifford circuits {C_i}_{i=1..M}.
//        Each C_i is the SAME GATE-SHAPE as C_target except each non-Clifford
//        R_z(theta) is replaced by R_z(k_j * pi/2), k_j drawn uniformly from
//        {0,1,2,3} (the four Clifford-on-pi/2-grid angles: 0->I, 1->S,
//        2->Z, 3->S^dagger). When K=0 in the replaced circuit (which is the
//        case for this module's whole training set since the target only has
//        ONE non-Clifford gate), every C_i is a pure Clifford circuit on
//        a stabilizer initial state, and <O>_C_i is EXACTLY computable in
//        polynomial time by Gottesman-Knill -- which is what makes CDR
//        scalable in the paper. For the simulator here we just evaluate
//        the exact 2^n state vector since n is small.
//
//    (3) For each training circuit C_i:
//          (a) Compute y_i := <O>_C_i^exact   (EXACT noise-free expectation,
//              from the simulator or from Gottesman-Knill on hardware).
//          (b) Run C_i on the NOISY device, record x_i := <O>_C_i^noisy
//              (sample-based on hardware; here = analytic depolarising
//              channel image on y_i).
//
//    (4) Linear ansatz (paper Eq. (2) -- the basic CDR fit):
//
//           f(x)  =  a  +  b * x                                         (*)
//
//        Analytic ordinary-least-squares solution (paper Eq. (5) and
//        the standard 1-D regression formula):
//
//           b  =  Sum_i (x_i - x_bar) (y_i - y_bar)  /
//                 Sum_i (x_i - x_bar)^2
//           a  =  y_bar  -  b * x_bar                                    (**)
//
//        (paper also discusses an extended-feature variant f(x) =
//        a + b1*x + b2*x^2 etc. -- we use the 1-D base form, the headline.)
//
//    (5) Apply the fit to the target circuit's noisy expectation:
//
//           <O>_target^mitigated  =  a  +  b * <O>_target^noisy            (***)
//
//  CLAIM 1 (closed-form at zero noise; the F1 falsifier):
//      If the noise channel is the identity, then x_i = y_i for every i,
//      so the regression of {(y_i, y_i)} gives b = 1, a = 0 to machine
//      precision (any one-to-one regression on collinear data does).
//      Then <O>_target^mitigated  =  0  +  1 * <O>_target^exact  =
//      <O>_target^exact -- the noise-free value passes through unchanged.
//
//  CLAIM 2 (variance-reduction; the F2 falsifier headline of the paper):
//      Under a global depolarising channel of strength p (the simplest
//      noise model), <O>_C^noisy = (1-p) <O>_C^exact for ANY traceless
//      Pauli O (since Tr(O * I/2^n) = 0). So the (x,y) training points
//      lie on the LINE x = (1-p) y exactly, and OLS recovers b = 1/(1-p),
//      a = 0 to machine precision. Then <O>_target^mitigated  =
//      (1/(1-p)) * (1-p) * <O>_target^exact  =  <O>_target^exact -- a
//      PERFECT mitigation on this noise model. The paper's gate-level noise
//      model is richer (it has both coherent and incoherent components, so
//      MSE_mitigated > 0 in general -- but still small compared to the raw
//      noisy MSE), and the headline MSE-reduction holds.
//
//      For OUR analytic-depolarising mock: MSE_raw = average over test
//      circuits of ((1-p) y_i - y_i)^2 = p^2 * <y_i^2>; MSE_mitigated -> 0
//      at machine precision (within the cancellation-error of the linear
//      regression). The falsifier F2 thus enforces MSE_mit <= MSE_raw on
//      the held-out test set (a non-trivial sanity check on the regression
//      pipeline; the equality version 'MSE_mit = 0' is the F3 stronger
//      check at the lower p=0.05 leg).
//
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  HONEST SCOPE  (@D g1 / @D g3 / @F f1 ; ceiling = 2^n state-vector wall)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  This module is an EXACT 2^n-amplitude state-vector simulation (pure-hexa
//  engine_aer) of the IDEAL Clifford Data Regression protocol of Czarnik-
//  Arrasmith-Coles-Cincio 2021. The "noise" model is the textbook analytic
//  depolarising-channel image on the EXACT noiseless <O> -- a deliberate
//  textbook simplification chosen so that the F1 (identity fit at p=0) and
//  F2/F3 (mitigated-MSE < raw-MSE) falsifiers can be evaluated at machine
//  precision, with NO sampling error and NO hardware-noise modelling. The
//  module is:
//
//   - NOT a real-QPU CDR run. There is no T_1/T_2 decoherence, no leakage,
//     no readout calibration error, no SPAM, no per-gate crosstalk, no
//     coherent calibration drift. The depolarising channel is a textbook
//     simplification (paper §III.B uses a much richer gate-level noise model
//     extracted from hardware; that is OUT OF SCOPE for this module and never
//     claimed). On real hardware the (x_i, y_i) cloud has BOTH bias (which
//     the linear regression captures) and shot-noise scatter (which the
//     regression averages out at the cost of finite-sample regression error
//     -- not modelled here, but stated honestly).
//
//   - NOT the asymptotic / large-n or large-M-training-set regime. The
//     paper's headline scaling claim (CDR's mitigated-MSE drops faster than
//     1/M_training) is paper-side; our F1-F5 verdict is a numerical witness
//     on ONE registered configuration (n=4, M_train=64, M_test=32, two
//     noise strengths). The closed-form depolarising channel makes
//     MSE_mitigated -> 0 (modulo regression-cancellation noise) on our
//     mock, NOT on real hardware where MSE_mit > 0 and falls 1/M-ish.
//
//   - NOT a duplicate of any existing qmirror module. Sibling-axis check:
//       * stabilizer/  +  surface_code_d3/  +  stabilizer-extent/  +
//         magic-stabilizer-renyi/  : Clifford / stabilizer-formalism /
//         nonstabilizerness MEASURES. None of these is error MITIGATION.
//       * process_tomography/  +  tomography/  : channel + state
//         tomography. Reconstructs noise channels but does NOT mitigate
//         a single expectation.
//       * symmetry-adjusted-shadows/  : symmetry-projector error
//         mitigation under classical shadows. Different mitigation axis
//         (symmetry projector, NOT training-set linear regression);
//         orthogonal to CDR.
//       * rpe-gate-calib/  : single-gate phase CALIBRATION (HL-RPE),
//         NOT observable mitigation.
//       * chemistry_vqe/  +  overlap-adapt-vqe/  +  vqd-excited-cs/  :
//         ground / excited-state energy estimation, not mitigation.
//     CDR is the *training-set linear regression on near-Clifford circuits*
//     error-mitigation axis -- distinct from all of the above. NEW axis.
//
//   - NOT a guarantee on adversarial noise. The CDR paper's mitigation
//     theorem (Eq. (5)) assumes the noise channel ACTS THE SAME WAY on
//     the training circuits as on the target. For the depolarising mock
//     this is true by construction; on real hardware it is an empirical
//     assumption that the paper validates only on the tested device.
//
//   - NOT the extended-feature variant. The paper also mentions
//     f(x) = a + b1 * x + b2 * x^2 + ... + b_d * x^d for higher-order
//     fits; we use the 1-D base form f(x) = a + b * x (paper Eq. (2)),
//     which is what the paper's headline F1-F2 falsifiers exercise.
//
//   - NOT noisy in the regression itself. We never inject finite-shot
//     noise into the training expectations; on real hardware those are
//     sample-based (variance ~ 1/N_shots), and the regression itself
//     introduces a finite-sample regression error (variance ~ sigma_eps^2
//     / (M * var(x)) per the standard OLS textbook); both are paper-side
//     and NOT modelled here.
//
//  Genuine ceiling: the 2^n state-vector memory wall for the SIMULATOR
//  (n <= 26-28 generically; this module caps at n = 8 for a comfortable
//  selftest budget). The CDR PROTOCOL itself scales to large n on hardware
//  because the training-set evaluation is Gottesman-Knill polynomial for
//  Clifford-only circuits; the 2^n wall here is the SIM-engine wall, not
//  a protocol wall, and is stated honestly.
//
//  Reachable-n (n=4) and reachable-M (M_train=64, M_test=32) results --
//  the 5 falsifier invariants and the slope/intercept/MSE numbers -- are
//  claimed exactly, never down-played. The qmirror hexa-lang interpreter
//  wall is ~30-60s at n=4 / M_train=64 / M_test=32 on Mac.
//
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  FILE OWNERSHIP / DROP-IN COMPAT  (@D g7)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  NEW sibling module. Does NOT touch engine_aer / qrng / chsh / iit_mip
//  external signatures (read-only consumer of state_vector + gates). Pure-
//  hexa runtime; NO .py / qiskit / qiskit-aer / qiskit-nature / pyscf /
//  pyphi dependency (@D g5). Falsifier-first marker emission (@D g6) --
//  the FAILED.marker write path runs BEFORE the pass marker.
//
//  Touches NO shared files: not hexa.toml, not AGENTS.tape, not cli/,
//  not CHANGELOG.md, not MODULE/, not README.md, not any other module.
//
// ── hexa quirks honored ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//   - >= / <= banned -- strict < / > / == only (use !(a<b) for >=).
//   - struct names cannot start with _.
//   - apply_single mutates state.re_h / state.im_h in place; pass a fresh
//     state_zero(n) at every circuit start; free at the end of each run.
//   - no `break` -- flag-driven while loops.
//   - power-of-two via while loop (no builtin).
//   - log() is natural log (ln); not needed here.
//   - exec("date +%s").trim() for unix timestamps (no now_unix).

use "../../engine_aer/module/state_vector.hexa"
use "../../engine_aer/module/gates.hexa"

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §1  SCALAR HELPERS
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn cdr_absf(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn cdr_max(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return b }
    return a
}

fn cdr_pi() -> float { return 3.141592653589793 }

// finite-check: an IEEE-754 NaN is the only value that is NOT equal to
// itself; +/- Inf is detected by  abs(x) > FINITE_MAX. We return 1 for
// finite, 0 for NaN/Inf.
fn cdr_is_finite(x: float) -> int {
    if x != x { return 0 }                   // NaN
    let big = 1.0e300
    if x > big { return 0 }                  // +Inf
    if x < (0.0 - big) { return 0 }          // -Inf
    return 1
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §2  DETERMINISTIC LCG  (no live QRNG -- reproducible seed)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  Identical LCG idiom as page-curve-scrambler / symmetry-adjusted-shadows /
//  recursive-qaoa-maxcut: state is a 31-bit positive integer, advanced by
//  state' = (1103515245 * state + 12345) mod 2^31. We use it ONLY to draw
//  the training-set Clifford angles k_j in {0,1,2,3} and the test-set angle
//  k_test; the noise model is analytic and has NO stochasticity.

fn cdr_lcg_next(s: int) -> int {
    return (s * 1103515245 + 12345) & 2147483647
}

// Draw an int in [0, k). Returns (new_state, value).
struct LcgInt {
    state: int,
    v:     int
}

fn cdr_lcg_int(s_in: int, k: int) -> LcgInt {
    let s2 = cdr_lcg_next(s_in)
    // map to [0, k) via the high bits (the low bits of an LCG are weak;
    // the top bit is the strongest -- divide by 2^31 then multiply by k).
    let u = to_float(s2) / 2147483648.0
    let v = to_int(u * to_float(k))
    let v2 = if v < 0 { 0 } else { if v < k { v } else { k - 1 } }
    return LcgInt { state: s2, v: v2 }
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §3  EXACT <Z_q> EXPECTATION ON A STATE VECTOR
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  <Z_q>_psi  =  Sum_i  sgn(bit_q of i)  |psi_i|^2
//
//  with sgn = +1 if bit_q = 0 (|0> eigenvalue +1) and -1 if bit_q = 1.
//  This is exact at machine precision (no sampling).

fn cdr_expect_z(sv: StateVector, q: int) -> float {
    let n = sv.n_qubits
    let mut dim = 1
    let mut kk = 0
    while kk < n { dim = dim * 2; kk = kk + 1 }
    let mut acc = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < dim {
        let bit = (i >> q) & 1
        let r = farr_get(sv.re_h, i)
        let im = farr_get(sv.im_h, i)
        let p = r * r + im * im
        let sgn = if bit == 0 { 1.0 } else { 0.0 - 1.0 }
        acc = acc + sgn * p
        i = i + 1
    }
    return acc
}

// <psi|psi> -- the norm-squared diagnostic for the F5 falsifier.
fn cdr_norm_sq(sv: StateVector) -> float {
    let n = sv.n_qubits
    let mut dim = 1
    let mut kk = 0
    while kk < n { dim = dim * 2; kk = kk + 1 }
    let mut acc = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < dim {
        let r = farr_get(sv.re_h, i)
        let im = farr_get(sv.im_h, i)
        acc = acc + r * r + im * im
        i = i + 1
    }
    return acc
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §4  PARAMETERIZED CIRCUIT (n=4, depth 6, 18 ops, ONE non-Clifford R_z)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  Target structure (chosen for non-trivial <Z_0> variance across the
//  training-set Clifford-angle replacements -- the R_z phase must be
//  converted to a real-amplitude shift in the Z basis on q0 by a
//  post-R_z basis-change. Putting H BEFORE R_z (so the rotation acts on
//  a |+>-like superposition) then H AFTER R_z (basis change back) makes
//  <Z_0> = cos(theta) -- a genuine theta-dependent target. Adding extra
//  Clifford structure makes the target non-trivial but keeps the
//  training-set spread):
//
//      Layer 1:  H on q0                        (|+>_0 -- the R_z rotation
//                                                axis becomes effective)
//      Layer 2:  R_z(theta) on q0               (THE ONE non-Clifford gate)
//      Layer 3:  H on q0                        (basis change back; after
//                                                this q0 is in cos(theta/2)
//                                                |0> - i sin(theta/2) |1>
//                                                product -- <Z_0> on q0
//                                                alone is exactly cos(theta))
//      Layer 4:  CNOT(0, 1)                     (q0 control, q1 target --
//                                                entangles q0/q1 but does
//                                                NOT change ρ_0 since q0
//                                                is the control)
//      Layer 5:  H on q2, H on q3               (Clifford background on
//                                                the spectator qubits)
//      Layer 6:  CNOT(0, 2)                     (q0 control, q2 target)
//      Layer 7:  CNOT(2, 3)                     (Clifford entangler on
//                                                spectators)
//      Layer 8:  S on q1                        (Clifford phase)
//
//  Total ops: 1 H + 1 R_z + 1 H + 1 CX + 2 H + 1 CX + 1 CX + 1 S = 9 ops,
//  depth 8. All gates are Clifford EXCEPT the R_z(theta) on q0. For the
//  target we use theta = pi/5 (non-multiple-of-pi/2 -- a hard non-Clifford
//  T-like angle); for the training set we replace it with R_z(k*pi/2) for
//  k in {0,1,2,3} (Clifford angles 0 -> I, 1 -> S, 2 -> Z, 3 -> S^dagger
//  up to global phase). So <Z_0>_k = cos(k*pi/2) = {+1, 0, -1, 0} for
//  k in {0, 1, 2, 3} -- three distinct values, giving a strictly positive
//  training-set var(x) (the OLS regression is well-defined).
//
//  Why this layout produces a CLEAN theta-dependent <Z_0> on the target:
//  the design rule (after debugging at #2026-05-17) is that q0 must be
//  the *control* of every downstream CNOT, NOT the target. A controlled-
//  unitary CNOT(0, j) does NOT change the reduced density matrix ρ_0 of
//  the CONTROL qubit (Tr_j[CNOT_{0,j} (ρ_0 (x) ρ_j) CNOT_{0,j}^dag] = ρ_0
//  because the CNOT is diagonal in the q0 basis, so Tr_j on j sums over
//  q0-diagonal-preserving terms). So <Z_0> after layer 3 -- which is
//  cos(theta) on the cos(theta/2)|0> - i sin(theta/2)|1> state -- is
//  preserved by all subsequent CNOT(0,j) and any single-qubit Clifford
//  on j != 0. This makes the target <Z_0> exactly cos(theta_target) =
//  cos(pi/5) ~ 0.8090 -- a clean non-trivial anchor.
//
//  An EARLIER (debug-superseded) circuit had CNOT(j, 0) entanglers
//  AFTER the R_z(theta), which collapsed ρ_0 to I/2 when the control
//  qubits were in |+> states (a CNOT with a |+>-control TARGET gets
//  a maximally-mixed reduced state). The fix was to switch the entangler
//  direction: q0 stays the control throughout.

fn cdr_run_circuit(theta_rz: float, n: int) -> StateVector {
    // n must be 4 for the registered selftest, but the function is
    // n-parameterised in case someone re-runs at n=6 or n=8 later.
    let mut sv = state_zero(n)
    let h = gate_h()
    let s = gate_s()
    let rz = gate_rz(theta_rz)

    // Layer 1: H on q0 (|+>_0; R_z rotation axis is now X/Y of q0)
    sv = apply_single(sv, h.re, h.im, 0, n)
    // Layer 2: R_z(theta) on q0  (THE ONE non-Clifford gate)
    sv = apply_single(sv, rz.re, rz.im, 0, n)
    // Layer 3: H on q0 (basis change back; <Z_0> at this point is exactly
    //   cos(theta) on q0 alone)
    sv = apply_single(sv, h.re, h.im, 0, n)
    // Layer 4: CNOT(0, 1) -- q0 CONTROL, q1 target. Entangles q0/q1
    //   without disturbing <Z_0> (ρ_0 is unchanged by CNOT-from-control).
    if n > 1 {
        sv = apply_cnot(sv, 0, 1, n)
    }
    // Layer 5: H on q2, H on q3 (Clifford background on spectators)
    if n > 2 {
        sv = apply_single(sv, h.re, h.im, 2, n)
    }
    if n > 3 {
        sv = apply_single(sv, h.re, h.im, 3, n)
    }
    // Layer 6: CNOT(0, 2) -- q0 CONTROL, q2 target. More q0-rooted
    //   entanglement; ρ_0 still unchanged.
    if n > 2 {
        sv = apply_cnot(sv, 0, 2, n)
    }
    // Layer 7: CNOT(2, 3) (Clifford entangler on spectators)
    if n > 3 {
        sv = apply_cnot(sv, 2, 3, n)
    }
    // Layer 8: S on q1 (Clifford phase on q1 -- adds an imaginary
    //   component to the entangled amplitudes elsewhere in the register)
    if n > 1 {
        sv = apply_single(sv, s.re, s.im, 1, n)
    }

    return sv
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §5  DEPOLARISING-CHANNEL MOCK  (analytic, machine-precision)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  The global depolarising channel
//      rho  ->  (1 - p) * rho  +  p * I / 2^n
//  acts on a traceless Pauli observable O by
//      <O>_noisy  =  Tr( O  [ (1 - p) rho + p I / 2^n ] )
//                 =  (1 - p) Tr(O rho)  +  p * Tr(O) / 2^n
//                 =  (1 - p) <O>_exact
//  since Tr(O) = 0 for any traceless Pauli (single- or multi-qubit). The
//  noise channel is therefore EXACTLY captured by a scalar rescaling
//  x = (1 - p) y -- the analytic mock the falsifier matrix is built on.
//
//  NOTE: this is the simplest noise model. The Czarnik 2021 paper uses
//  a richer gate-level Pauli + amplitude-damping noise model (§III.B);
//  that model is out of scope per the honest-scope block above.

fn cdr_apply_depolarising(exact_o: float, p: float) -> float {
    let one_minus_p = 1.0 - p
    return one_minus_p * exact_o
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §6  TRAINING-SET CONSTRUCTION + OLS REGRESSION
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  Build M training circuits. Each draws k_j in {0,1,2,3} from the LCG;
//  runs the circuit with R_z(k_j * pi/2); evaluates y_j = <Z_0>_exact;
//  applies the depolarising-channel mock to get x_j = (1 - p) y_j; checks
//  norm-drift; accumulates the (x_j, y_j) cloud.

struct CdrTrainingSet {
    xs:           [float],
    ys:           [float],
    n_circuits:   int,
    worst_drift:  float,    // worst |<psi|psi> - 1| across all M circuits
    state_after:  int       // final LCG state (so test set is independent)
}

fn cdr_build_training_set(n: int, m: int, p: float, seed0: int) -> CdrTrainingSet {
    let pi_2 = cdr_pi() / 2.0
    let mut xs = []
    let mut ys = []
    let mut state = seed0
    let mut worst = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < m {
        let d = cdr_lcg_int(state, 4)
        state = d.state
        let k = d.v                              // in {0,1,2,3}
        let theta = to_float(k) * pi_2           // Clifford angle
        let sv = cdr_run_circuit(theta, n)
        let y_exact = cdr_expect_z(sv, 0)
        let x_noisy = cdr_apply_depolarising(y_exact, p)
        let nrm = cdr_norm_sq(sv)
        let drift = cdr_absf(nrm - 1.0)
        if drift > worst { worst = drift }
        let _ = state_free(sv)
        xs = xs.push(x_noisy)
        ys = ys.push(y_exact)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return CdrTrainingSet {
        xs: xs, ys: ys,
        n_circuits: m,
        worst_drift: worst,
        state_after: state
    }
}

// Held-out test set: M_test fresh circuits drawn with the LCG state INHERITED
// from the training-set construction (so the seeds don't overlap). Each test
// circuit replaces the non-Clifford R_z(theta_target) with a NEAR-Clifford
// rotation R_z(theta_target + delta_j) where delta_j = (k_j_test - 1.5) *
// pi/8 introduces a small non-Clifford offset. This makes the test set
// distinct from the training set (different theta values), while keeping it
// close to the same circuit family. We then compute (y_exact, y_noisy =
// (1-p) y_exact, y_mitigated = a + b * y_noisy) and the MSEs.
//
// NOTE: we use NEAR-CLIFFORD test circuits (not strict Clifford) so the
// test set is non-degenerate w.r.t. the training set. Strict-Clifford test
// circuits would be drawn from the SAME pool as training, making the
// in-distribution generalisation trivial.

struct CdrTestSet {
    y_exacts:    [float],
    y_noisies:   [float],
    y_mitigats:  [float],
    n_circuits:  int,
    worst_drift: float,
    mse_raw:     float,
    mse_mit:     float,
    state_after: int
}

fn cdr_run_test_set(n: int, m_test: int, p: float,
                    theta_target: float, slope: float, intercept: float,
                    seed_start: int) -> CdrTestSet {
    let mut y_exs = []
    let mut y_no  = []
    let mut y_mi  = []
    let mut state = seed_start
    let mut worst = 0.0
    let mut sse_raw = 0.0
    let mut sse_mit = 0.0
    let pi = cdr_pi()
    let mut i = 0
    while i < m_test {
        // Near-Clifford offset in [-pi/8 .. +pi/8] step pi/16 around theta_target.
        let d = cdr_lcg_int(state, 16)
        state = d.state
        let delta = (to_float(d.v) - 7.5) * (pi / 64.0)    // ~ in (-pi/8.5 .. pi/8.5)
        let theta = theta_target + delta
        let sv = cdr_run_circuit(theta, n)
        let y_exact = cdr_expect_z(sv, 0)
        let y_noisy = cdr_apply_depolarising(y_exact, p)
        let y_mit   = intercept + slope * y_noisy
        let nrm = cdr_norm_sq(sv)
        let drift = cdr_absf(nrm - 1.0)
        if drift > worst { worst = drift }
        let _ = state_free(sv)
        y_exs = y_exs.push(y_exact)
        y_no  = y_no.push(y_noisy)
        y_mi  = y_mi.push(y_mit)
        let err_raw = y_noisy - y_exact
        let err_mit = y_mit   - y_exact
        sse_raw = sse_raw + err_raw * err_raw
        sse_mit = sse_mit + err_mit * err_mit
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mf = to_float(m_test)
    return CdrTestSet {
        y_exacts: y_exs, y_noisies: y_no, y_mitigats: y_mi,
        n_circuits: m_test, worst_drift: worst,
        mse_raw: sse_raw / mf,
        mse_mit: sse_mit / mf,
        state_after: state
    }
}

// Analytic 1-D OLS: returns (slope, intercept, var_x, n_points).
//
//   slope     =  Sum (x_i - x_bar)(y_i - y_bar)  /  Sum (x_i - x_bar)^2
//   intercept =  y_bar - slope * x_bar
//
// var_x is reported so the caller can detect a degenerate (all-identical x)
// training set: if var_x == 0 we cannot regress, the slope is undefined, and
// the F1 falsifier will trip via the NaN/Inf check (F4).

struct OlsFit {
    slope:     float,
    intercept: float,
    var_x:     float,
    n_points:  int
}

fn cdr_ols_fit(xs: [float], ys: [float]) -> OlsFit {
    let n = len(xs)
    let nf = to_float(n)
    let mut sx = 0.0
    let mut sy = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        sx = sx + xs[i]
        sy = sy + ys[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    let xbar = sx / nf
    let ybar = sy / nf
    let mut sxy = 0.0
    let mut sxx = 0.0
    let mut j = 0
    while j < n {
        let dx = xs[j] - xbar
        let dy = ys[j] - ybar
        sxy = sxy + dx * dy
        sxx = sxx + dx * dx
        j = j + 1
    }
    let var_x = sxx / nf
    let slope = if sxx == 0.0 { 0.0 } else { sxy / sxx }
    let intercept = ybar - slope * xbar
    return OlsFit { slope: slope, intercept: intercept,
                    var_x: var_x, n_points: n }
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §7  HEADLINE RUN  (config -> verdict)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
//  Config: registered parameters of the falsifier-first selftest.
//   n         = 4 qubits
//   m_train   = 64 training circuits (Czarnik 2021 §IV.A uses M ~ 50-200)
//   m_test    = 32 held-out test circuits
//   seed0     = 7361 (the qmirror LCG seed convention)
//   p_zero    = 0.0  (F1: identity fit at zero noise)
//   p_high    = 0.1  (F2: mitigated <= raw at p = 0.1)
//   p_low     = 0.05 (F3: mitigated < 0.95 * raw at low noise)
//   theta_tg  = pi / 5  (non-Clifford target angle)

struct CdrCfg {
    n:        int,
    m_train:  int,
    m_test:   int,
    seed0:    int,
    p_zero:   float,
    p_high:   float,
    p_low:    float,
    theta_tg: float
}

fn cdr_default_cfg() -> CdrCfg {
    return CdrCfg {
        n:        4,
        m_train:  64,
        m_test:   32,
        seed0:    7361,
        p_zero:   0.0,
        p_high:   0.1,
        p_low:    0.05,
        theta_tg: cdr_pi() / 5.0
    }
}

struct CdrVerdict {
    ok:                int,
    verdict:           str,
    // F1 (identity at p=0)
    slope_zero:        float,
    intercept_zero:    float,
    var_x_zero:        float,
    f1_passed:         int,
    // F2 (mitigated MSE <= raw MSE at p=0.1) + slope/intercept at p_high
    slope_high:        float,
    intercept_high:    float,
    target_exact:      float,
    target_noisy_h:    float,
    target_mit_h:      float,
    mse_raw_h:         float,
    mse_mit_h:         float,
    f2_passed:         int,
    // F3 (mitigated < 0.95 * raw at p=0.05)
    slope_low:         float,
    intercept_low:     float,
    target_noisy_l:    float,
    target_mit_l:      float,
    mse_raw_l:         float,
    mse_mit_l:         float,
    mse_ratio_l:       float,
    f3_passed:         int,
    // F4 (no NaN / Inf)
    f4_passed:         int,
    // F5 (norm drift across all circuits)
    worst_drift:       float,
    f5_passed:         int,
    // diagnostic
    wall_seconds:      float,
    engine:            str,
    message:           str
}

fn cdr_run(cfg: CdrCfg) -> CdrVerdict {
    let t0 = to_int(exec("date +%s").trim())

    // ── (1) Target-circuit expectation: the noise-free <O>_target.
    let sv_tgt = cdr_run_circuit(cfg.theta_tg, cfg.n)
    let target_exact = cdr_expect_z(sv_tgt, 0)
    let target_norm = cdr_norm_sq(sv_tgt)
    let _ = state_free(sv_tgt)
    let target_drift = cdr_absf(target_norm - 1.0)

    // ── (2) ZERO-NOISE leg: build training set, fit OLS, check F1.
    let train_z = cdr_build_training_set(cfg.n, cfg.m_train, cfg.p_zero, cfg.seed0)
    let fit_z = cdr_ols_fit(train_z.xs, train_z.ys)
    let slope_z_ok = cdr_absf(fit_z.slope - 1.0) < 0.000000001
    let intercept_z_ok = cdr_absf(fit_z.intercept) < 0.000000001
    let f1 = if slope_z_ok == true && intercept_z_ok == true { 1 } else { 0 }

    // ── (3) HIGH-NOISE leg (p = 0.1): training set + test set + MSE.
    let train_h = cdr_build_training_set(cfg.n, cfg.m_train, cfg.p_high, cfg.seed0)
    let fit_h = cdr_ols_fit(train_h.xs, train_h.ys)
    let target_noisy_h = cdr_apply_depolarising(target_exact, cfg.p_high)
    let target_mit_h   = fit_h.intercept + fit_h.slope * target_noisy_h
    let test_h = cdr_run_test_set(cfg.n, cfg.m_test, cfg.p_high,
                                  cfg.theta_tg, fit_h.slope, fit_h.intercept,
                                  train_h.state_after)
    // F2: mitigated MSE must be NO LARGER than raw MSE on held-out test.
    // We add a tiny tol to absorb cancellation noise at high p.
    let f2 = if test_h.mse_mit < test_h.mse_raw + 0.000000001 { 1 } else { 0 }

    // ── (4) LOW-NOISE leg (p = 0.05): same protocol; F3 = 5% margin.
    let train_l = cdr_build_training_set(cfg.n, cfg.m_train, cfg.p_low, cfg.seed0)
    let fit_l = cdr_ols_fit(train_l.xs, train_l.ys)
    let target_noisy_l = cdr_apply_depolarising(target_exact, cfg.p_low)
    let target_mit_l   = fit_l.intercept + fit_l.slope * target_noisy_l
    let test_l = cdr_run_test_set(cfg.n, cfg.m_test, cfg.p_low,
                                  cfg.theta_tg, fit_l.slope, fit_l.intercept,
                                  train_l.state_after)
    let mse_ratio_l = if test_l.mse_raw > 0.0 {
                         test_l.mse_mit / test_l.mse_raw
                     } else { 1.0 }
    let f3 = if mse_ratio_l < 0.95 { 1 } else { 0 }

    // ── (5) F4: all slope / intercept values must be finite.
    let f4 = if cdr_is_finite(fit_z.slope) == 1
              && cdr_is_finite(fit_z.intercept) == 1
              && cdr_is_finite(fit_h.slope) == 1
              && cdr_is_finite(fit_h.intercept) == 1
              && cdr_is_finite(fit_l.slope) == 1
              && cdr_is_finite(fit_l.intercept) == 1 { 1 } else { 0 }

    // ── (6) F5: worst <psi|psi> drift across all circuits we ran.
    let mut worst = target_drift
    if train_z.worst_drift > worst { worst = train_z.worst_drift }
    if train_h.worst_drift > worst { worst = train_h.worst_drift }
    if train_l.worst_drift > worst { worst = train_l.worst_drift }
    if test_h.worst_drift > worst  { worst = test_h.worst_drift }
    if test_l.worst_drift > worst  { worst = test_l.worst_drift }
    let f5 = if worst < 0.000000001 { 1 } else { 0 }

    let pass_all = if f1 == 1 && f2 == 1 && f3 == 1 && f4 == 1 && f5 == 1
                   { 1 } else { 0 }
    let verdict = if pass_all == 1 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" }
    let msg = if pass_all == 1 {
        "all F1-F5 invariants cleared"
    } else {
        "at least one falsifier triggered -- see slope/intercept/MSE numbers"
    }

    let t1 = to_int(exec("date +%s").trim())
    let wall = to_float(t1 - t0)

    return CdrVerdict {
        ok: 1, verdict: verdict,
        slope_zero: fit_z.slope, intercept_zero: fit_z.intercept,
        var_x_zero: fit_z.var_x, f1_passed: f1,
        slope_high: fit_h.slope, intercept_high: fit_h.intercept,
        target_exact: target_exact,
        target_noisy_h: target_noisy_h, target_mit_h: target_mit_h,
        mse_raw_h: test_h.mse_raw, mse_mit_h: test_h.mse_mit,
        f2_passed: f2,
        slope_low: fit_l.slope, intercept_low: fit_l.intercept,
        target_noisy_l: target_noisy_l, target_mit_l: target_mit_l,
        mse_raw_l: test_l.mse_raw, mse_mit_l: test_l.mse_mit,
        mse_ratio_l: mse_ratio_l, f3_passed: f3,
        f4_passed: f4,
        worst_drift: worst, f5_passed: f5,
        wall_seconds: wall,
        engine: "pure-hexa engine_aer / 16-amp state-vector / CDR (Czarnik 2021)",
        message: msg
    }
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §8  MARKER  (falsifier-first; @D g6 -- FAILED.marker BEFORE pass marker)
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn cdr_emit_marker(passed: int, body: str) -> int {
    let ts = exec("date +%s").trim()
    let qm_root = env("QMIRROR_ROOT")
    let root = if qm_root.len() > 0 { qm_root } else { exec("pwd").trim() }
    let marker_dir = root + "/state/markers"
    let _mk = exec("mkdir -p " + marker_dir + " 2>/dev/null")
    let suffix = if passed == 1 { ".marker" } else { "_FAILED.marker" }
    let path = marker_dir + "/clifford_data_regression_" + ts + suffix
    let _w = exec("echo '" + body + "' > '" + path + "'")
    println("  marker: " + path)
    return 0
}

fn cdr_emit_from_verdict(v: CdrVerdict, cfg: CdrCfg) -> int {
    let body =
        "clifford_data_regression selftest;" +
        " n=" + str(cfg.n) +
        " m_train=" + str(cfg.m_train) +
        " m_test=" + str(cfg.m_test) +
        " seed0=" + str(cfg.seed0) +
        " theta_target=" + str(cfg.theta_tg) +
        " target_exact=" + str(v.target_exact) +
        " slope_zero=" + str(v.slope_zero) +
        " intercept_zero=" + str(v.intercept_zero) +
        " var_x_zero=" + str(v.var_x_zero) +
        " slope_high=" + str(v.slope_high) +
        " intercept_high=" + str(v.intercept_high) +
        " target_noisy_h=" + str(v.target_noisy_h) +
        " target_mit_h=" + str(v.target_mit_h) +
        " mse_raw_h=" + str(v.mse_raw_h) +
        " mse_mit_h=" + str(v.mse_mit_h) +
        " slope_low=" + str(v.slope_low) +
        " intercept_low=" + str(v.intercept_low) +
        " mse_raw_l=" + str(v.mse_raw_l) +
        " mse_mit_l=" + str(v.mse_mit_l) +
        " mse_ratio_l=" + str(v.mse_ratio_l) +
        " worst_drift=" + str(v.worst_drift) +
        " F1=" + str(v.f1_passed) +
        " F2=" + str(v.f2_passed) +
        " F3=" + str(v.f3_passed) +
        " F4=" + str(v.f4_passed) +
        " F5=" + str(v.f5_passed) +
        " wall=" + str(v.wall_seconds) + "s ; " + v.message

    // Falsifier-first: FAILED.marker BEFORE pass.
    if v.verdict != "PASS" {
        let _ = cdr_emit_marker(0, "FAIL " + body)
        return 0
    }
    let _ = cdr_emit_marker(1, "PASS " + body)
    return 1
}

fn cdr_selftest() -> int {
    let cfg = cdr_default_cfg()
    let v = cdr_run(cfg)
    if v.ok != 1 {
        let _ = cdr_emit_marker(0, "FAIL run-error ; " + v.message)
        return 0
    }
    return cdr_emit_from_verdict(v, cfg)
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  §9  MAIN
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[qmirror/clifford-data-regression] Clifford Data Regression error mitigation")
    println("  paper  = Czarnik, Arrasmith, Coles, Cincio,")
    println("           Error mitigation with Clifford quantum-circuit data,")
    println("           Quantum 5, 592 (2021) / arXiv:2005.10189.")
    println("  protocol = §IV.A + Eq. (2) (linear ansatz) + Eq. (5) (OLS solve).")
    println("  scope  = EXACT 2^n state vector, n=4; M_train=64 + M_test=32;")
    println("           analytic depolarising-channel mock x_i = (1-p) y_i; OLS")
    println("           a = y_bar - b * x_bar,  b = Sxy / Sxx.")
    println("  ceil   = n<=8 (2^n state-vector envelope); CDR protocol itself")
    println("           scales because Clifford training is Gottesman-Knill")
    println("           polynomial -- the 2^n wall is the SIM-engine wall, not")
    println("           a CDR-protocol wall.")
    println("")

    let cfg = cdr_default_cfg()
    let v = cdr_run(cfg)
    if v.ok != 1 {
        println("  ERROR: " + v.message)
        let _ = cdr_emit_marker(0, "FAIL run-error ; " + v.message)
        println("__QMIRROR_CLIFFORD_DATA_REGRESSION__ FAIL")
        return
    }

    println("  --- config ---")
    println("    n=" + str(cfg.n) + "  M_train=" + str(cfg.m_train) +
            "  M_test=" + str(cfg.m_test) + "  seed0=" + str(cfg.seed0))
    println("    theta_target = pi/5 = " + str(cfg.theta_tg) +
            " (non-Clifford)   p_zero=" + str(cfg.p_zero) +
            "  p_high=" + str(cfg.p_high) + "  p_low=" + str(cfg.p_low))
    println("    target_exact <Z_0> = " + str(v.target_exact))
    println("")
    println("  --- F1 zero-noise leg (p=0; identity fit) ---")
    println("    slope     = " + str(v.slope_zero) +
            "       (target = 1.0; tol 1e-9)")
    println("    intercept = " + str(v.intercept_zero) +
            "    (target = 0.0; tol 1e-9)")
    println("    var(x)    = " + str(v.var_x_zero) +
            "    (must be > 0 for non-degenerate OLS)")
    println("")
    println("  --- F2/F3 high/low-noise legs (test-set MSE comparison) ---")
    println("    p=0.10:")
    println("      slope_h     = " + str(v.slope_high))
    println("      intercept_h = " + str(v.intercept_high))
    println("      target_noisy = " + str(v.target_noisy_h) +
            "    target_mit = " + str(v.target_mit_h))
    println("      MSE_raw      = " + str(v.mse_raw_h) +
            "    MSE_mitigated = " + str(v.mse_mit_h))
    println("      F2 (MSE_mit <= MSE_raw)                       = " +
            str(v.f2_passed))
    println("    p=0.05:")
    println("      slope_l     = " + str(v.slope_low))
    println("      intercept_l = " + str(v.intercept_low))
    println("      target_noisy = " + str(v.target_noisy_l) +
            "    target_mit = " + str(v.target_mit_l))
    println("      MSE_raw      = " + str(v.mse_raw_l) +
            "    MSE_mitigated = " + str(v.mse_mit_l))
    println("      MSE ratio (mit / raw)                          = " +
            str(v.mse_ratio_l))
    println("      F3 (MSE_mit < 0.95 * MSE_raw)                  = " +
            str(v.f3_passed))
    println("")
    println("  --- F4/F5 sanity ---")
    println("    F4 (slope/intercept finite -- no NaN / Inf)      = " +
            str(v.f4_passed))
    println("    worst <psi|psi> drift across all circuits        = " +
            str(v.worst_drift))
    println("    F5 (norm drift < 1e-9)                            = " +
            str(v.f5_passed))
    println("")
    println("    wall                                              = " +
            str(v.wall_seconds) + "s")
    println("    engine                                            = " + v.engine)
    println("    verdict                                           = " + v.verdict)
    println("    msg                                               = " + v.message)
    println("")

    let mres = cdr_emit_from_verdict(v, cfg)
    if mres == 1 {
        println("[qmirror/clifford-data-regression] SELFTEST PASS")
        println("  (Zero-noise OLS fit recovers the identity (slope=1, intercept=0)")
        println("   to machine precision; the linear regression a + b * <O>_noisy")
        println("   reduces test-set MSE at both p=0.1 and p=0.05 by the analytic")
        println("   depolarising-channel inverse; <psi|psi> conserved.)")
        println("__QMIRROR_CLIFFORD_DATA_REGRESSION__ PASS")
    } else {
        println("[qmirror/clifford-data-regression] SELFTEST FAIL (see *_FAILED.marker)")
        println("__QMIRROR_CLIFFORD_DATA_REGRESSION__ FAIL")
    }
}
